'''Oi Shrine''' (おいじんじゃ, いひじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in {{jalink|Tottori Prefecture|Q133935}}, {{jalink|Yazu District|Q1043163}}, {{jalink|Wakasa Town|Q1156116}}. The enshrined deity is Ame-no-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto, and the shrine crest is the crossed-arrow motif. It is a {{jalink|Shikinaisha}}, and its former shrine rank was {{jalink|Village shrine|Q134917284}}.

=== Overview ===
This shrine was established by descendants of Ame-no-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto to enshrine their ancestral deity. It is an ancient shrine with over a thousand years of history, listed in the {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}} ({{jalink|927|Q30470}}) of the {{jalink|Heian period|Q193292}}. It stands on a hill at the entrance to the Yadora district, beyond the {{jalink|Hattō River|Q11391449}} from {{jalink|Wakasa-juku|Q11616547}}.

In ancient times it was called “'''Oi-no-miya'''” and was located in Ichinomiya Valley (Fukada), but according to tradition it was relocated to Yaotoshi Valley (= Yadora = Yadora), the place where an arrow shot from the shrine grounds by {{jalink|Takenouchi no Sukune|Q1073668}} is said to have landed. At the foot of the hill stands Japan’s largest {{jalink|nobori banner|Q1068772}}.

=== Shrine grounds ===
; Japan’s largest nobori banner
It was erected on October 8 of the first year of the Heisei era as a reconstruction of Oi Shrine’s “five-tan nobori,” which existed until around {{jalink|1945|Q5240}} (Shōwa 20).
A Yadora-grown {{jalink|cedar}} (100 years old, 31 m tall) is used as the pole. The banner measures 26.8 m in height and 1.8 m in width, equivalent in area to 30 tatami mats.
The calligraphy was done by {{jalink|Shigenobu Sakano|Q11425611}} for the banner, {{jalink|Yuji Nishio|Q11627787}} for the hoisting platform, and {{jalink|Kenji Takemoto}} for the commemorative monument.

; One of Japan’s largest wooden torii gates
Erected on January 30 of Heisei 23 to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the accession of {{jalink|Emperor Akihito}}.
As with the banner pole, it was built using Yadora-grown {{jalink|cedar}} (over 80 years old, milled from trees 18 m tall).
Its dimensions are 10.8 m in height and 9.2 m in width, ranking it among the top five wooden torii gates in Japan (as of May, Heisei 23).
The shrine name plaque calligraphy was done by {{jalink|Norie Nagano}}, head of the Tottori Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines. The initiator and overall person in charge was {{jalink|Masayuki Iino}}, head parish representative of Oi Shrine.

