'''Oi Shrine''' (おいじんじゃ, いひじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Tottori Prefecture|Q133935|WD=Q133935|1=Tottori Prefecture}}, {{ill|lt=Yazu District|Q1043163|WD=Q1043163|1=Yazu District, Tottori}}, {{ill|lt=Wakasa Town|Q1156116|WD=Q1156116|1=Wakasa, Tottori}}. The enshrined deity is Ame-no-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto, and the shrine crest is the crossed-arrow motif. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former shrine rank was {{ill|lt=Village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Overview ===
This shrine was established by descendants of Ame-no-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto to enshrine their ancestral deity. It is an ancient shrine with over a thousand years of history, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) of the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}. It stands on a hill at the entrance to the Yadora district, beyond the {{ill|lt=Hattō River|Q11391449|WD=Q11391449|1=Hatto river}} from {{ill|lt=Wakasa-juku|Q11616547|WD=Q11616547|1=Wakasa-juku}}.

In ancient times it was called “'''Oi-no-miya'''” and was located in Ichinomiya Valley (Fukada), but according to tradition it was relocated to Yaotoshi Valley (= Yadora = Yadora), the place where an arrow shot from the shrine grounds by {{ill|lt=Takenouchi no Sukune|Q1073668|WD=Q1073668|1=Takenouchi no Sukune}} is said to have landed. At the foot of the hill stands Japan’s largest {{ill|lt=nobori banner|Q1068772|WD=Q1068772|1=Nobori}}.

=== Shrine grounds ===
; Japan’s largest nobori banner
It was erected on October 8 of the first year of the Heisei era as a reconstruction of Oi Shrine’s “five-tan nobori,” which existed until around {{ill|lt=1945|Q5240|WD=Q5240|1=1945}} (Shōwa 20).
A Yadora-grown {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=cedar|1=UNKNOWN}} (100 years old, 31 m tall) is used as the pole. The banner measures 26.8 m in height and 1.8 m in width, equivalent in area to 30 tatami mats.
The calligraphy was done by {{ill|lt=Shigenobu Sakano|Q11425611|WD=Q11425611|1=Shigenobu Sakano}} for the banner, {{ill|lt=Yuji Nishio|Q11627787|WD=Q11627787|1=Yūji Nishio}} for the hoisting platform, and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kenji Takemoto|1=UNKNOWN}} for the commemorative monument.

; One of Japan’s largest wooden torii gates
Erected on January 30 of Heisei 23 to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the accession of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Emperor Akihito|1=UNKNOWN}}.
As with the banner pole, it was built using Yadora-grown {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=cedar|1=UNKNOWN}} (over 80 years old, milled from trees 18 m tall).
Its dimensions are 10.8 m in height and 9.2 m in width, ranking it among the top five wooden torii gates in Japan (as of May, Heisei 23).
The shrine name plaque calligraphy was done by {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Norie Nagano|1=UNKNOWN}}, head of the Tottori Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines. The initiator and overall person in charge was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Masayuki Iino|1=UNKNOWN}}, head parish representative of Oi Shrine.

